                <img alt='Marco Schwartz' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/ff00bb813ba5f3567535b791f1487620?s=60&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D60&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-60 photo' height='60' width='60' />            </div>

            <!-- display the comment -->
            <div class='comment_content'>
                <header class="comment-header">
                    <cite class="author_name heading" itemprop="creator" itemscope="itemscope" itemtype="https://schema.org/Person" ><a href="http://www.marcoschwartz.com" ><cite class="comment_author_name" itemprop="name" >Marco Schwartz</cite></a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>                    
                    <!-- display the comment metadata like time and date-->
                        <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
                            <a href="http://www.openhomeautomation.net/arduino-vs-raspberry-pi-which-platform-is-the-best-for-home-automation/#comment-5038">
                                <time  itemprop="commentTime" itemscope="itemscope" datetime="2013-04-29T01:52:15+00:00" >
                                    July 4, 2013 at 3:32 am                                </time>
                            </a>
                        </div>
                </header>

                <!-- display the comment text -->
                <div class='comment_text entry-content-wrapper clearfix'  itemprop="commentText" >
                <p>Hi,</p>
<p>Sure you can code in C/C++ on the Raspberry Pi. For your extra modules, you always have to be sure that they are working with the 3.3V output of the Pi. Otherwise you will need some logic converter circuits.</p>
                                <a class='comment-reply-link' href='/arduino-vs-raspberry-pi-which-platform-is-the-best-for-home-automation/?replytocom=5038#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-5038", "5038", "respond", "282")'>Reply</a>                </div>
